msgid "<0>/var/lib/multiview/hls</0> — the HLS output directory. Back it with a named volume so a sidecar (or your host) can serve the playlist and segments."
msgstr "<0>/var/lib/multiview/hls</0> — the HLS output directory. Back it with a named volume so a sidecar (or your host) can serve the playlist and segments."

#: src/pages/docs/OverviewPage.tsx:71
msgid "<0>Composite once, fan out many.</0> The canvas is encoded once per rendition and the same packets feed every transport, rather than re-encoding per destination."
msgstr "<0>Composite once, fan out many.</0> The canvas is encoded once per rendition and the same packets feed every transport, rather than re-encoding per destination."

#: src/pages/docs/OverviewPage.tsx:57
msgid "<0>Continuous output.</0> One monotonic output clock produces a valid, correctly-timestamped frame every tick, independent of any input."
msgstr "<0>Continuous output.</0> One monotonic output clock produces a valid, correctly-timestamped frame every tick, independent of any input."

#: src/pages/docs/OverviewPage.tsx:78
msgid "<0>Control never back-pressures the engine.</0> The management API, realtime streams, and preview are best-effort and physically incapable of stalling the output path."
msgstr "<0>Control never back-pressures the engine.</0> The management API, realtime streams, and preview are best-effort and physically incapable of stalling the output path."

#: src/pages/docs/ConfigPage.tsx:196
msgid "<0>fit</0> controls scaling: <1>fill</1>, <2>contain</2>, <3>cover</3>, <4>none</4>, or <5>scale_down</5>."
msgstr "<0>fit</0> controls scaling: <1>fill</1>, <2>contain</2>, <3>cover</3>, <4>none</4>, or <5>scale_down</5>."

#: src/pages/docs/FeaturesPage.tsx:80
msgid "<0>HLS / file output.</0> Writes a playlist and segments to disk. This is the path the quick-start uses and that works today."
msgstr "<0>HLS / file output.</0> Writes a playlist and segments to disk. This is the path the quick-start uses and that works today."

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/LatencyPage.tsx:84
msgid "<0>HLS:</0> 6–30 s — players deliberately start several segments behind the live edge. <1>LL-HLS</1> brings this to roughly 2–5 s with partial segments."
msgstr "<0>HLS:</0> 6–30 s — players deliberately start several segments behind the live edge. <1>LL-HLS</1> brings this to roughly 2–5 s with partial segments."

#: src/pages/docs/OverviewPage.tsx:64
msgid "<0>Last-good-frame resilience.</0> Each tile rides a live / stale / reconnecting / no-signal state machine; a failing input cannot block the compositor."
msgstr "<0>Last-good-frame resilience.</0> Each tile rides a live / stale / reconnecting / no-signal state machine; a failing input cannot block the compositor."

#: src/pages/docs/FeaturesPage.tsx:99
msgid "<0>Live RTSP / NDI / RTMP / SRT servers and push.</0> The network output servers are not yet wired into the run command."
msgstr "<0>Live RTSP / NDI / RTMP / SRT servers and push.</0> The network output servers are not yet wired into the run command."

#: src/pages/docs/FeaturesPage.tsx:90
msgid "<0>Low-latency HLS.</0> Partial-segment HLS for lower glass-to-glass latency."
msgstr "<0>Low-latency HLS.</0> Partial-segment HLS for lower glass-to-glass latency."

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/LatencyPage.tsx:59
msgid "<0>MPEG-TS / UDP multicast:</0> well under a second on a managed network (no recovery buffering at all)."
msgstr "<0>MPEG-TS / UDP multicast:</0> well under a second on a managed network (no recovery buffering at all)."

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/LatencyPage.tsx:53
msgid "<0>NDI:</0> about a frame on a fast LAN — the lowest of the supported transports."
msgstr "<0>NDI:</0> about a frame on a fast LAN — the lowest of the supported transports."

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/TimingSyncPage.tsx:129
msgid "<0>Output clock</0> — decides <1>when</1> each frame is emitted (monotonic, fixed cadence)."
msgstr "<0>Output clock</0> — decides <1>when</1> each frame is emitted (monotonic, fixed cadence)."

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/LatencyPage.tsx:78
msgid "<0>RTMP:</0> a few seconds of TCP and player buffering."
msgstr "<0>RTMP:</0> a few seconds of TCP and player buffering."

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/TransportsPage.tsx:90
msgid "<0>RTSP vs NDI in one paragraph:</0> RTSP is a pull-style protocol for reaching a specific device by address — ideal for fixed camera installs, works across routed networks, and spends very little bandwidth because the camera's compressed stream is reused as-is. NDI is a discovery-based fabric for a production LAN — sources appear by name, latency is near-frame, and quality is mezzanine-grade, but it expects a fast local network (a 1080p59.94 feed is roughly 100 Mb/s) and does not traverse the internet. Choose RTSP to monitor cameras where they are; choose NDI when the multiview sits inside a production network that already speaks it."
msgstr "<0>RTSP vs NDI in one paragraph:</0> RTSP is a pull-style protocol for reaching a specific device by address — ideal for fixed camera installs, works across routed networks, and spends very little bandwidth because the camera's compressed stream is reused as-is. NDI is a discovery-based fabric for a production LAN — sources appear by name, latency is near-frame, and quality is mezzanine-grade, but it expects a fast local network (a 1080p59.94 feed is roughly 100 Mb/s) and does not traverse the internet. Choose RTSP to monitor cameras where they are; choose NDI when the multiview sits inside a production network that already speaks it."

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/LatencyPage.tsx:65
msgid "<0>RTSP:</0> typically 0.2–1 s — a small network buffer plus the camera's encoder delay."
msgstr "<0>RTSP:</0> typically 0.2–1 s — a small network buffer plus the camera's encoder delay."

#: src/pages/docs/ApiPage.tsx:114
msgid "<0>Server-Sent Events</0> (fallback) at <1>/api/v1/events</1> — one-way, for environments where a WebSocket cannot be used."
msgstr "<0>Server-Sent Events</0> (fallback) at <1>/api/v1/events</1> — one-way, for environments where a WebSocket cannot be used."

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/LatencyPage.tsx:71
msgid "<0>SRT:</0> the configured latency window (commonly 120 ms to a few seconds) — you are explicitly buying loss recovery with delay."
msgstr "<0>SRT:</0> the configured latency window (commonly 120 ms to a few seconds) — you are explicitly buying loss recovery with delay."

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/TimingSyncPage.tsx:141
msgid "<0>Timecode</0> — a per-frame <1>label</1> (HH:MM:SS:FF). Two feeds can carry identical timecode and still be out of phase — which is why genlock/PTP exist alongside it."
msgstr "<0>Timecode</0> — a per-frame <1>label</1> (HH:MM:SS:FF). Two feeds can carry identical timecode and still be out of phase — which is why genlock/PTP exist alongside it."

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/TimingSyncPage.tsx:135
msgid "<0>Wall clock</0> — says <1>what time of day</1> it is (for clocks and stream metadata)."
msgstr "<0>Wall clock</0> — says <1>what time of day</1> it is (for clocks and stream metadata)."

#: src/pages/docs/ApiPage.tsx:108
msgid "<0>WebSocket</0> (primary) at <1>/api/v1/ws</1> — bidirectional, used for the live UI."
msgstr "<0>WebSocket</0> (primary) at <1>/api/v1/ws</1> — bidirectional, used for the live UI."

